---
/**
 * About page.
 *
 * Who built this and why. First-person, honest, nonlinear.
 * The story of how Alice came about, told the way it actually happened.
 */
import PublicLayout from '../layouts/layPublic.astro';
---

<PublicLayout title="Alice -- About" active="about" description="Who built Alice, why, and how it came about.">

<article class="about">

  <header class="ab-hero">
    <h1>Anthony Guzzardo</h1>
    <p class="ab-role">Software engineer. Builder. Sole participant.</p>
  </header>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <p>I am a software engineer. I haven't written a line of code by hand in the last four months. I interact with AI daily, it's how I spend most of the day. I can see how it's shaping my thinking process. Turning more ideas into apps regularly. Working on paid work and side projects concurrently. I like to write and read, don't read much anymore, and have always been a fluent typist.</p>

    <p>This has nothing to do with what led me to Alice but it will help me to say that once I've explained how Alice came about.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <h2>How this started</h2>

    <p>Initially I wanted to create a co-op science forum that would bring together scientists to discover new theories and perhaps get funding. Mainstream collaborative science into an online portal that could support it. A Reddit-meets-seed-money working data treasure trove for STEM fields, primarily physics and mathematics.</p>

    <p>It's not obvious why that interests me. I am quite poor at math, and it's one of my insecurities. I can never be and will never be good enough at it and it would be a waste of time for me to try and study complex systems, as I would spend too much time to get not even very good. But I still like to follow it and that drives me to exist near it.</p>

    <p>Eventually a website was created which I still look at here and there. One page in particular I kept focusing on. It's essentially pulling from archival websites daily. arXiv, NASA, a few other places, and ranking the most relevant trending things in science. Black holes, quantum gravity, Dyson spheres, solar sails. That sort of thing. A cron job runs every night and I kind of let that one ride.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <h2>Then a different project</h2>

    <p>A new idea came to mind. An Einstein-esque platform that a smart individual could use to unlock parts of their brain, perhaps contribute new theories. The idea was to journal, journal, journal with deep questions, and in doing so the system would start to be able to theorize on its own. Valid contributions to science. It would generate novel questions. I called them suppressed questions. Then I added a prediction layer. All LLM-generated, based on input and initially a few small behavioral signals. The input would listen and listen and not bias the experimenter until at some point something clicked and it could develop a breakthrough.</p>

    <p>Then I learned the system was flawed. It was a circular loop and self-graded. Moreover, LLMs are good at reasoning and logic but cannot generate genuinely novel questions. So I shifted into a mathematical approach only, which started to morph the project into a different idea entirely.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <h2>What it became</h2>

    <p>Less about creating a super genius to contribute to science. More about something that could map a person's cognitive thinking capacity through context and input signaling, measured very precisely. This could lead to the most robust longitudinal study of a person as their own control group. Unforeseen. Lots of value to analyze out of that.</p>

    <p>Then I started to dig into the research and realized partly why it hadn't been done before. The aging population typically measured for behavioral signals is studied to detect MCI, not much else, and they weren't typing fluent. They were hen-pecking. Then it occurred to me there would be a window approaching of typing-fluent people we could start to track, and over the course of 20 years the amassment of data would be invaluable.</p>

    <p>Somewhere in between I started to research signal-to-noise and how AI, autocomplete, and other assistive tools have started to affect how we process information. Every modality people interact with via input typically uses these noise-introducing features. It's all gamified and very gratifying. So it seemed more and more important that we could create a repository of clean data.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <h2>Where it is now</h2>

    <p>I continue to test it out on myself and hope that the results are significant enough to map to existing population baselines. Back to my typing. I have always been a good typist, so this is probably one of the best modalities to analyze me through. I acknowledge the need for modality-agnostic instruments, but that comes later.</p>

    <p>I built the entire signal pipeline. Native Rust for the numerical estimation. PostgreSQL for the longitudinal storage. Six signal families, 120+ metrics per session, same-day calibration, personal baselines, empirical coupling discovery. I am both the engineer and the sole participant. That's a methodological confound and I name it openly. The instrument is designed to produce the data that would enable validation. The validation requires participants who did not build it. That's the next step.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section">
    <h2>What I need</h2>

    <p>Domain expertise. I can build the instrument. I cannot validate it alone. Cognitive scientists, digital biomarker researchers, psycholinguists who can evaluate whether the signals this instrument computes correspond to the constructs they are intended to measure. The engineering is ahead of the science by design. The science needs to catch up. That requires collaboration.</p>
  </section>

  <section class="ab-section ab-close">
    <div class="ab-contact">
      <a href="mailto:anthony@mrfoxco.com" class="ab-email">anthony@mrfoxco.com</a>
    </div>
